                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d418">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">840.515 Gold Bloc/80: Telegram (part air)</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Consul at Geneva</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Gilbert</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Geneva</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1935-05-20T17:00:00+01:00"
                            >May 20, 1935—5 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received May 22—6:22 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>192. The Council today adopted the report of its <hi rend="italic"
                        >rapporteur</hi> on work of the Joint Committee on Clearing Agreements<note
                        n="10" xml:id="d418fn10">For text of report, see League of Nations, <hi
                            rend="italic">Official Journal</hi>, June 1935, p. 597.</note> in which
                        <pb facs="0637" n="535" xml:id="pg_535"/> governments are invited to
                    consider the conclusions reached by the Committee and as far as possible take
                    account of them in regard to their own countries and financial policy. The
                    importance of the report was stressed by the Australian and French
                    delegates.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Gilbert</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
